{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95 for all (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and then restricted to the incident window and to resource-related KPIs (excluding mesh/istio). The top results show widespread anomalous KPI points (many pairs had anomaly_count = window_count = 31). Notable findings: a container memory RSS metric for frontend-2 slightly exceeded its P95 (small relative breach), but many metrics named container_memory_failures.* (and system.io.* and system.process.zombie.num) have global_P95=0 and nonzero values in the window — these indicate events that are normally zero and therefore likely meaningful. Nodes node-6, node-5 and node-4 appear in these KPI names (e.g., container.node-6.container_memory_failures.*, container.node-5.container_memory_rss, system.process.zombie.num on node-4). error_logs are concentrated between 15:45:39 and 15:50:03 CST (Asia/Shanghai). To localize the root cause we must identify which component(s) show the largest number of distinct resource KPIs flagged as anomalous and the earliest anomaly times per component so we can correlate with traces/logs. Current results imply node-level memory failure events (container_memory_failures) across multiple services on node-6 and node-5, but we need a compact per-component ranking to pick candidates for trace/log inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, recompute global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the entire file. Then filter metric.csv to the incident window '2022-03-21 15:30:00' through '2022-03-21 16:00:00' Asia/Shanghai. Apply the same KPI filters as before (exclude KPIs containing 'mesh' or 'istio' or 'trace'; keep KPIs containing resource keywords such as 'cpu', 'memory', 'rss', 'heap', 'jvm', 'load', 'transmit', 'receive', 'retransmit', 'packet', 'latency', 'drop', 'disk', 'io', 'read', 'write', 'space', 'network', 'error', 'process'). For each cmdb_id present after filtering compute: (a) number of distinct kpi_name with anomaly_count>0 (value >= global_P95) within the window, (b) total anomaly data point count across all its KPIs in-window, (c) earliest anomaly timestamp among its anomalies (Asia/Shanghai), and (d) list of up to 10 distinct kpi_name that had anomalies for that cmdb_id. Return a compact table of the top 10 cmdb_id ordered by number of distinct anomalous KPIs desc, and include the four fields above. Also return the total number of cmdb_id with at least one anomalous KPI (single-line aggregate). Limit list of KPI names per cmdb_id to 10." 
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis shows many anomalous traces concentrated on frontend-* and checkoutservice-* instances, with earliest trace anomalies at 2022-03-21 15:30:00 CST. Metric analysis (resource-focused) showed widespread anomalies across many services but prominently many container KPIs indicating container_memory_failures and node-level KPIs (e.g., system.io.*, system.process.zombie.num) tied to node-6 and node-5. Error logs are concentrated later in the window (15:45:39–15:50:03 CST) and reference frontend and cartservice, suggesting user-facing errors appeared after metric anomalies began. According to the diagnosis rules, node-level memory/failure KPIs (container_memory_failures) that are normally zero and turned non-zero are strong candidates for real faults. To confirm and localize the root cause we need (1) a focused metric anomaly summary for node-6 and node-5 (global thresholds must be computed from the full metric series before filtering) showing earliest anomalous KPI timestamps and severity, and (2) an error_logs summary in the incident window to correlate when user-facing errors started and which services were affected. This will help determine whether the root cause is node-level (node-6 or node-5), the exact occurrence time (earliest anomalous metric timestamp), and the reason (memory failures or similar).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Do two compact analyses in one run (use metric.csv and error_logs.csv):\n1) Error logs summary: filter error_logs.csv to the incident window '2022-03-21 15:30:00' through '2022-03-21 16:00:00' Asia/Shanghai. For each cmdb_id present, compute count of error log rows, earliest error timestamp (Asia/Shanghai), and return up to 5 example messages per cmdb_id. Return the top 20 cmdb_id ordered by count desc.\n2) Node-focused metric anomaly summary: using metric.csv, first compute global P95 of value for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the entire file (no pre-filter). Then filter metric.csv to the incident window '2022-03-21 15:30:00' through '2022-03-21 16:00:00' Asia/Shanghai. Focus only on cmdb_id equal to 'node-6' and 'node-5'. For each of these two nodes, for each kpi_name present in the window compute: window_count, anomaly_count (value >= global_P95; if global_P95==0 treat value>0 as anomaly), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (Asia/Shanghai) or null, max_value_in_window, and max_value_minus_P95. Then for each node return a compact table of its anomalous KPIs (limit to top 20 by anomaly_count desc then max_value_minus_P95 desc) with columns: node_cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, window_count, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, max_value_minus_P95. Also return a one-line aggregate for each node: number of distinct kpi_name with anomaly_count>0 and the earliest anomaly timestamp across all its KPIs.\nKeep all outputs compact (limit lists to top 20 rows and example messages to 5). Do not print full time series." 
}

